# SPECTRAL PCM — Assessment Standards

## Assessment Architecture

| Assessment | Format | When | Pass Mark | Duration |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Daily knowledge checks | 10 MCQ per lesson | End of each lesson | 70% (7/10) | 10 min |
| Day 1 end-of-day review | 20 MCQ | End of Day 1 | 70% (14/20) | 20 min |
| Day 2 end-of-day review | 20 MCQ | End of Day 2 | 70% (14/20) | 20 min |
| Final written assessment | 50 MCQ + 3 short-answer | End of Day 3 | 80% (see below) | 75 min |
| Scenario assessment | DS observation rubric | Days 4–5 | Satisfactory | Ongoing |

## Final Assessment Pass Criteria

To receive SPECTRAL PCM Course Completion certificate:
- MCQ component: ≥ 40/50 (80%)
- Short-answer component: ≥ 10/15 (2 of 3 questions at satisfactory standard)
- **Both** components must be passed independently — a perfect MCQ score does not compensate for a failed short-answer

## Bloom's Taxonomy Distribution

### Final Assessment (50 MCQ)
| Level | Questions | % | Descriptor |
|---|---|---|---|
| Remember | 8 | 16% | Recall of specific facts, definitions, platform specs |
| Understand | 12 | 24% | Explain mechanism, describe relationship |
| Apply | 15 | 30% | Use knowledge in a given scenario |
| Analyse | 10 | 20% | Break down a situation, identify components/causes |
| Evaluate | 5 | 10% | Judge options, justify a decision |

Note: Create level not assessed in written format — this is the scenario days.

### Bloom's by Day (lesson checks)
| Day | Primary levels | Rationale |
|---|---|---|
| Day 1 | Remember + Understand | Establishing the knowledge base — orientation phase |
| Day 2 | Understand + Apply | Technical depth requires application, not just recall |
| Day 3 | Apply + Analyse + Evaluate | Operational synthesis — this is where the course pays off |

## Final Assessment — Short-Answer Rubric

### Marking Scale (per question, 5 marks)
| Mark | Standard |
|---|---|
| 5 | All key points present, operationally grounded, accurate |
| 4 | All key points present, minor error or missing operational grounding |
| 3 | Most key points present, one significant gap |
| 2 | Partial understanding, significant gaps or one major error |
| 1 | Minimal relevant content, attempt made |
| 0 | No relevant content or not attempted |

### Pass threshold per question
- Satisfactory: ≥ 3/5
- Unsatisfactory: ≤ 2/5
- Both must be satisfactory to pass the short-answer component

## Scenario Assessment Rubric (Days 4–5)

DS observes and scores each student / team across four decision points per scenario:

| Decision Point | Criteria | Weight |
|---|---|---|
| Situational Awareness | Did they correctly interpret the sensor picture before deciding? | 25% |
| Decision Quality | Was the decision logical given available information (not perfect information)? | 30% |
| Justification | Could they articulate *why* they decided that, citing doctrine or TTPs? | 25% |
| Adaptation | When injected with new information, did they update their decision appropriately? | 20% |

**Pass standard:** Satisfactory (≥ 60%) across all four criteria. A single 0% on any criterion triggers a mandatory debrief regardless of overall score.

## Assessment Question Bank Requirements

The question bank must contain 3× the number of questions needed for any assessment (minimum 150 MCQ for a 50-question final). This allows:
- Randomisation between student groups (prevents answer sharing)
- Version A / Version B for retake management
- Annual refresh without full rebuild

## Retake Policy

- Daily knowledge checks: no formal retake — DS decision on student readiness to progress
- End-of-day reviews: one retake available, different question set
- Final assessment: one retake within 30 days, different question set, same pass standard
- Scenario assessment: re-run one scenario (DS selects which), assessed by same rubric

